04102nam a22006975i 9780691184845DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911848457 a10.1515/97806911848452doi  a(DE-B1597)501669  a(OCoLC)1076458037  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE302.J442 7aHIS0360302bisacsh04a973.460921 aJefferson, Thomas, eauthor.10aPapers of Thomas Jefferson. n33, pThe Papers of Thomas Jefferson, Volume 33 ; 17 February to 30 April 1801 /cThomas Jefferson; Barbara B. Oberg. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPapers of Thomas Jefferson ;v3300tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tEDITORIAL METHOD AND APPARATUS -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tJEFFERSON CHRONOLOGY -- tFEBRUARY 1801 -- tMARCH 1801 -- tAPRIL 1801 -- tAppendix I: Lists of Appointments and Removals -- tAppendix II: Notations by Jefferson on Senate Documents -- tAppendix III: Letters Not Printed In Full -- tAppendix IV: Letters Not Found -- tINDEX  aUnder normal circumstances, Thomas Jefferson would have had more than two months to prepare for his presidency. However, since the House of Representatives finally settled a tied electoral vote only on 17 February 1801, he had two weeks. This book, which covers the two-and-a-half-month period from that day through April 30, is the first of some twenty volumes that will document Jefferson's two terms as President of the United States. Here, Jefferson drafts his Inaugural Address, one of the landmark documents of American history. In this famous speech, delivered before a packed audience in the Senate Chamber on March 4, he condemns "political intolerance" and asserts that "we are all republicans: we are all federalists," while invoking a policy of "friendship with all nations, entangling alliances with none." Jefferson appoints his Cabinet members and deals with the time-consuming process of sifting through the countless appeals and supporting letters of recommendation for government jobs as he seeks to reward loyal Republicans and maintain bipartisan harmony at the same time. Among these letters is one from Catharine Church, who remarks that only women, excluded as they are from political favor or government employment, can be free of "ignorant affectation" and address the president honestly. Jefferson also initiates preparations for a long cruise by a squadron of American warships, with an unstated expectation that their destination will probably be the Barbary Coast of the Mediterranean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh1 aOberg, Barbara B., eeditor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691184845zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691184845.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN